# 2. PRIMARY USER GOALS
 
## Rider Goals
 
Riders are the only user class in this system. The backend has no driver entity. Every person using this platform is attempting to travel from one location to another and share that journey with others going the same way.
 
### Urgency Level
 
Moderate to high. University riders typically have class schedules, meal times, or appointment commitments. They are not browsing; they have a destination and a time constraint. The average acceptable wait for a university commuter is 10–15 minutes from the time they open the app to the time they expect the ride to materialize.
 
### Primary Goals (in priority order)
 
- Get to destination on time — the overriding concern. All UX decisions that conflict with this must be questioned.
 
- Know the cost upfront — fare ambiguity is a trust-destroyer. Riders want to see their fare share before committing.
 
- Verify route and co-riders — riders want to know who they are sharing with and whether the route is reasonable.
 
- Cancel easily if plans change — cancellation must be low-friction and consequence-transparent.
 
- Be informed of status changes — especially co-rider cancellations and match results.
 
### Emotional Expectations
 
- When submitting a request: Mild anxiety. "Will I get a match in time?" The UI must immediately reassure them that the system is processing their request.
 
- While waiting: Growing impatience after 90 seconds. Must be countered with visible activity (animated status, progress indication, elapsed time).
 
- When matched: Relief and curiosity. "Who am I riding with? What route? How much?"
 
- During active trip: Relative calm. Fare share is known, route is set. Main concern is timely arrival.
 
- After completion: Satisfaction proportional to fare savings vs solo trip. Explicitly showing savings reinforces future use.
 
### Frustration Risks
 
| **Risk** | **Trigger** | **UX Mitigation** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| No match found | Sitting in PENDING state too long | Show elapsed time; display expected batch timing; allow easy cancel and re-submit |
| Unexpected re-queue | Co-rider cancellation | Proactive notification with explanation; show existing wait priority is preserved |
| Unclear fare | Seeing fare only after accepting match | Show estimated fare range during request creation |
| Route feels wrong | Detour to pick up co-rider | Show detour ratio clearly; explain each stop serves a co-rider |
| App left open too long | Session stale, data outdated | Polling architecture ensures data freshness; show "last updated" timestamp |
| Request auto-cancelled | Reached max pending cycles | Clear notification with reason; one-tap to re-submit with same parameters |
 
## Admin Goals
 
Admins are technical operators (developers in this demo context). Their goals are operational, not experiential.
 
- Verify the matching engine is running and producing results.
 
- Trigger manual matching cycles for testing and debugging.
 
- Inspect pending/matched/cancelled counts in real time.
 
- Review matching cycle logs to detect configuration issues or low-density periods.
 
- Confirm trip creation correctness after engine runs.
 
| **No Driver Role** The backend has no driver model. Do not design any driver-facing screen. The concept of "driver assignment" does not exist. Riders are grouped into shared trips; the logistics of who drives is outside the system scope. Do not imply otherwise in any UI copy. |
