# 3. USER MENTAL MODELS
 
## What Users Expect vs What the System Actually Does
 
Mental model mismatches are the primary source of UX failure in transportation apps. When the system behaves differently from what users expect, they lose trust rapidly. The following analysis maps each critical moment against the gap between user expectation and system reality.
 
### Ride Booking
 
| **What Users Expect** An Uber-like experience: tap, confirm, driver dispatched. Instant confirmation. Booking feels like a transaction that has been completed. | **System Reality** Request enters a queue. Matching runs in a batch cycle every 60 seconds. There is no immediate confirmation of a partner — only confirmation that the request was received. |
| --- | --- |
 
| **UX Bridge** Reframe the submission confirmation as "Your ride request is active." Not "Booking confirmed." The language must set the right expectation immediately — you have registered intent, not secured a ride. |
| --- |
 
### Ride Matching
 
| **What Users Expect** Matching happens in real-time. The system scans continuously and assigns a ride the moment a compatible partner exists. | **System Reality** Batch-based. The engine collects all pending requests and processes them together every 60 seconds. A user who submits 1 second after a batch starts waits up to 59 seconds for the next cycle. |
| --- | --- |
 
| **UX Bridge** Show a visible "Next match check in X seconds" countdown or a subtle pulse animation that communicates the system's active rhythm. Do not show a static spinner — that implies real-time processing and will cause users to think the app is stuck. |
| --- |
 
### Waiting
 
| **What Users Expect** Waiting means the app is broken or no rides exist. In traditional apps, waiting beyond 30 seconds usually means failure. Users will attempt to refresh, re-submit, or abandon. | **System Reality** Waiting is the designed state. Requests remain PENDING across multiple batch cycles. A request may legitimately wait 3–5 cycles (3–5 minutes) before finding a match during low-density periods. |
| --- | --- |
 
| **UX Bridge** Show elapsed waiting time, cycle count, and a reassurance message that updates progressively. At 2 minutes show "Still searching — the system checks every minute." At 4 minutes: "Expanding search parameters..." Do not let the waiting state feel static or broken. |
| --- |
 
### Route and Stops
 
| **What Users Expect** The route goes directly from their pickup to their destination. Any detour to collect a co-rider feels like an imposition — "why am I being taken out of my way?" | **System Reality** The matching engine enforces a maximum 30% detour ratio. Every detour is bounded, optimised, and a direct consequence of the shared cost savings. The fare module only charges for active on-board distance. |
| --- | --- |
 
| **UX Bridge** Always display the detour ratio as a percentage alongside the stop sequence. Pair it with the fare saving: "You're sharing 2 stops. Your detour is 12%. You save ₹47 vs. travelling alone." Make the trade-off explicit and obviously worthwhile. |
| --- |
 
### Cancellations
 
| **What Users Expect** Cancelling their own request is harmless. They also expect that cancelling during a matched state only affects them. | **System Reality** Cancelling a MATCHED request triggers a cascade: the entire trip is cancelled, and all co-riders are re-queued. This is the single biggest expectation mismatch in the system. |
| --- | --- |
 
| **UX Bridge** Before confirming a cancellation on a MATCHED request, display an explicit warning modal: "Cancelling your matched ride will also cancel the trip for your 2 co-riders. They will be placed back in the queue. Are you sure?" This transforms a silent cascade into an informed decision. |
