# 7. INFORMATION ARCHITECTURE
 
## Progressive Disclosure Strategy
 
Information should reveal itself at the moment it becomes relevant, not before. Showing fare before a match is found, or showing co-rider details before they are confirmed, creates expectation mismatches. Every piece of information should appear at its earliest useful moment — not its earliest technically available moment.
 
## Home / Request Form — Information Hierarchy
 
- Level 1 (immediately visible): Pickup and drop input fields. These are the only thing that matters.
 
- Level 2 (always visible): Preferred time picker. Clear label: "When do you want to depart?"
 
- Level 3 (below fold): Brief explanation of the matching model — one sentence. "We'll group you with nearby riders heading the same way."
 
- Level 4 (hidden, shown only on interaction): Autocomplete suggestions from Nominatim. The bounding box constraint means results are local — no explanation needed unless a user asks.
 
- Never shown: Raw coordinates, API endpoint URLs, technical validation rules (only show outcomes: "Pickup and drop cannot be the same location").
 
