## UX Priority Ranking
 
If time or effort is constrained, the following ranking determines what must be done before anything else:
 
- Waiting Screen with live elapsed time and cycling status messages. This is the highest-anxiety screen in the entire app. A poor waiting experience will cause users to abandon the app even if everything else works.
 
- Cancel confirmation modal with cascade warning for MATCHED state. Cascade cancellation is the most disruptive user event in the system. Informed users forgive the system; surprised users distrust it.
 
- Trip Screen fare share displayed above the fold before the map. Cost anxiety is the second highest trust barrier after waiting anxiety.
 
- Re-queue notification when co-rider cancels. Silent re-queuing is worse than the cancellation itself.
 
- State-driven routing and initialisation recovery. The app must return to the correct screen on refresh without data loss.
 
- Home form with Nominatim autocomplete that constrains to Patiala bounding box.
 
- Summary screen with savings comparison.
 
- Admin panel (demo use only, low urgency for user-facing experience).
 
## The Most Important User Moments
 
These are the moments that determine whether a user trusts and returns to the app:
 
| **Moment** | **Why It Matters** | **Success Criteria** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| First 5 seconds after submitting a request | Sets tone for entire waiting experience | User sees clear confirmation + reassurance message immediately |
| At 90 seconds of waiting | Impatience peak in non-instant systems | User sees elapsed time, cycle indicator, knows the system is working |
| Match notification | Highest emotional peak — relief + curiosity | Immediate, clear notification + smooth transition to Trip Screen |
| First view of fare share | Cost anxiety resolution moment | Fare is above the fold, paired with solo trip comparison |
| Co-rider cancellation event | Highest disruption moment | User is told immediately, reason is clear, re-queue is confirmed |
| Trip completion | Defines the lasting impression | Summary shows savings, feels like a reward for sharing |
 
## What Defines Success for This UX
 
This UX succeeds if a user who has never used the app can:
 
- Submit their first ride request without reading any documentation.
 
- Understand what is happening during the wait without becoming anxious.
 
- Trust that the fare shown to them is fair before they are committed to the trip.
 
- Know exactly what happened if a co-rider cancels, and know what to do next.
 
- Complete a trip and leave feeling they saved money compared to travelling alone.
 
This UX fails if any of the following occur:
 
- A user refreshes the page and loses their active ride request context.
 
- A user waits for 3 minutes with a static spinner and assumes the app has crashed.
 
- A user is surprised by a cascade cancellation with no warning.
 
- A user sees an empty Trip Screen because the route map did not load.
 
- A user cannot find the cancel button when they need it urgently.
 
| **Final Principle: Design for the Anxious User First** Every design decision should be evaluated through the lens of the most anxious possible user — someone who is late for class, has just been re-queued by a stranger's cancellation, and is not sure if the app is working. If that user can navigate the app calmly and confidently, every other user can too. |
